<section xml:id="sec-modeling-logarithms-and-exp-eq" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Logarithms and Exponential Equations</title>
<p>
  In <xref ref="sec-modeling-exponential"/>, we developed exponential models and used them to predict populations, values of assets, and quantities of radioactive elements at given times. In this section, we learn the tools to determine how long it will take to reach a given population, value or amount. We will solve for the exponent in exponential equations.
</p>
  <p>
    You have seen several functions in mathematics that are primarily used to "undo" other functions. For example, the opposite of squaring is taking the square root, and the opposite of cubing is taking the cube root. But what is the opposite of an expnential function in which there is a variable in the exponent?
  </p>
  <p>
  <md>
    <mrow> x^{2}=5\amp \Leftrightarrow x=\pm\sqrt{5}</mrow>
    <mrow> x^{3}=5\amp \Leftrightarrow x=\sqrt[3]{5}</mrow>
    <mrow> 10^{x}=5\amp  \Leftrightarrow x=???</mrow>
  </md>
</p>
 <p>
  This is where logarithms come in!
</p>
  
  
<subsection xml:id="logs-common-log">
<title>The Common Logarithm</title>

<p>The common logarithm, written <m>\log(x)</m>, answers the question, "what power do you raise 10 to in order to get <m>x</m>?"
</p>
<p>
For example, <m>\log (100) =2</m> because <m>10^{2}=100</m>. Similarly, <m>\log (1\,000\,000)=6</m> because <m>10^{6}=1\,000\,000</m>.
</p>
<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Evaluate <m>\log (1\, 000)</m> and <m>\log(10)</m> without a calculator.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <m>\log(1\,000)=3</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>\log(10)=1</m>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
  <p>
   You may be wondering how useful this common logarithm can be since it only works with powers of 10. We will make use of the <em>exponent property</em> for logarithms.
  </p>
  <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-common-log-exponent-property">
    <title>Common Logarithm Exponent Property</title>
    <p>
      <m>\log(b)^{x}=x\cdot \log(b)</m>
    </p>
  </assemblage>
<p> 
  We can use this fact to solve exponential equations, such as <m>120(1.04)^{t}=240</m>.
</p>
<p>
  The first step is to use algebra to isolate the exponential part, <m>(1.04)^{t}</m>.
</p>
<p>
<md>
  <mrow>\frac{120(1.04)^{t}}{120} \amp = \frac{240}{120} </mrow>
  <mrow>(1.04)^{t} \amp=2 </mrow>
</md>
</p>
<p>
  Now we take the common logarith of both sides of the equation and use the exponent property to simplify.
  <md>
    <mrow>\log(1.04)^{t} \amp=\log(2) </mrow>
    <mrow>t\cdot\log(1.04) \amp= \log(2) </mrow>
  </md>
</p>
<p>
  We now have <m>t</m> multiplied by <m>\log(1.04)</m>, so we can use division to solve for <m>t</m>.
  <md>
    <mrow>\frac{t\cdot \log(1.04)}{\log(1.04)} \amp=\frac{\log(2)}{\log(1.04)} </mrow>
    <mrow>t \amp\approx 17.67 </mrow>
  </md>
</p>
<p>
  
</p>
</subsection>

</section>